itative Health Research and Sex/Gender Sensitivity: A Scoping Review -- tPART FOUR Exemplifying Change (Health Policy and Practice) -- tCHAPTER TWELVE Social Influences on Injection Drug Use among a Community Sample of Sex Workers: Intersections of Structure and Agency across the Life Course -- tCHAPTER THIRTEEN Towards a Broader Conceptualization of Trans Women’s Sexual Health -- tCHAPTER FOURTEEN “Women and Madness” Revisited: The Promise of Intersectional and Mad Studies Frameworks -- tCHAPTER FIFTEEN The Intersecting Social and Structural Contexts of Navigating HIV Risk and Access to Care among Women -- tCHAPTER SIXTEEN Social Transformation and Urban Regeneration: Well-Being and Women’s Marginalization in Community Contexts -- tCHAPTER SEVENTEEN Violence against Women: Intersections of Health and Justice -- tCHAPTER EIGHTEEN Evolving Disability Scholarship and Activism in Canadian Contexts: Making Room for Intersectionality -- tCHAPTER NINETEEN Understanding Migrant Women’s Health: Looking through Intersectional, Gendered, and Human Rights Lenses -- tCHAPTER TWENTY An Intersectional Analysis of the Ontario Dementia Strategy -- tCHAPTER TWENTY-ONE Prioritizing Non-communicable Diseases at the Intersections: Global Action in the Canadian Context -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWomen’s Health in Canada considers the challenges relating to the conceptualization of women’s health. While emphasizing the importance of taking an intersectional approach to women’s healthcare, this book also focuses on the social and structural determinants at play. This revised and updated second edition brings together a collection of new chapters and contributors who collectively shed light on the problems and risks involved at perceiving women’s healthcare using a strickly "gender" or "sex" based lens. The book not only challenges the privileging of gender norms, but also deepens and extends intersectional theorizing and analysis of health care. Contributors foreground an understanding of power as it is mediated through a range of social relations based on gender, race, culture, ethnicity, sexuality, ability, class, geography, and the ways in which privilege and oppression intersect to shape health and system responses to health. This new edition includes updates on what is currently known about women’s health nationally, as well as internationally, and situates the chapters in the current Canadian health care and policy context. Scholarship is foregrounded in new developments in gender and intersectionality health research and policy in shaping responses to women’s health. Collectively, this volume explores the important histories and contemporary realities in women’s health experiences.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aMedical policyzCanada. 0aWomenxHealth and hygienezCanada. 0aWomen's health serviceszCanada. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Women's Health.2bisacsh  aCanadian health.  aHIV risks.  aIndigenous health.  aactivism.  adisability.  ahealth.  aintersectional feminism.  aintersectionality.  atrans women’s health.  aviolence against women.  awomen’s health in Canada.  awomen’s health.1 aAllan, Billie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBauer, Greta R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenoit, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBolte, Gabriele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChatterjee, Sabina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEtherington, Cole, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrisby, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato